[2] Bolivia (Santa Cruz): alert
Date: Wed 31 Jan 2007
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Los Tiempos.com, Bolivia [edited Mod.JT; transl. Mod.TY]
<http://www.lostiempos.com/noticias/31-01-07/31_01_07_nac1.php>

Bolivia (Santa Cruz): red alert
------------------------------
The Departmental [state equivalent - Mod.TY] Health Department (SEDES
[Spanish acronym]) confirmed yesterday [30 Jan 2007] that a
23-year-old woman died this past Friday [26 Jan 2007] due to dengue
hemorrhagic fever [DHF]. This is the 1st [DHF] death recorded in
Santa Cruz in the past 3 years. In 2003, 5 people lost their lives
from this disease according to the Epidemiological Unit.
Roberto Vargas, director of SEDES, informed us that due to this
situation, the task of elimination of the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_
has been strengthened with [the use] of 19 [insecticide] fogging
machines in rural and urban areas of the department.
This official indicated that he has been trying to communicate with
health authorities in Paraguay where dengue epidemics have been
reported. "We wish to exchange information in order to combat this
disease more effectively" he said.
With 47 confirmed cases of classical dengue fever and one of DHF in
Santa Cruz, as well as others in Cochabamba and Beni, the Vice
Minister of Health declared a red alert in the country to prevent the
spread of the disease, taking into account that rains and floods have
occurred due to El Nino [effects]. "We are on red alert due to the
possibility that the result of the constant rains [would lead to]
more disease cases, among them dengue. We are carrying out daily
epidemiological surveillance and taking necessary preventive
[actions], such as spraying" said Juan Nogales, Vice Minister of Health.
Yesterday [30 Jan 2007], the Beni Departmental Council issued a
declaration of state of emergency for the department, to facilitate
and put into action the attention needed by more than 2000 families
in riverine communities which have been affected by the alarming
increase in the waters of the Mamore and other rivers, over-topping
their banks.
[Santa Cruz is Bolivia's largest lowland city, hence concern about a
major dengue outbreak. A map of Bolivia can be accessed
at:<http://worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/samerica/bo.htm> - Mod. TY]
