[3] Bolivia (Beni)
Date: Fri 2 Feb 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: China View [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-02/03/content_5689540.htm>

Bolivia reports 7 new cases of dengue fever
---------------------------------------------------
Authorities from the regional Health Service said on Fri 2 Feb 2007,
that 7 new cases of dengue fever have been detected in recent days in
the northern Bolivian province of Beni.
Cesar Ligeron, head of the vector control program, urged residents to
work together to eliminate the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito that spreads dengue
[virus].
As intense rain in the region diluted the effect of insecticide, it
is almost useless to conduct spraying there, he said. Instead he
called on authorities from the regional capital Trinidad to clean up
and collect garbage in areas within the city that could help
[prevent] the spread of mosquitoes.
Ligeron said that his organization wanted daily reports on the
appearance of new cases and asked anyone who suspected they have
dengue to take a test provided by the National Tropical Diseases Service.
One person has died this year [2007] from hemorrhagic dengue, in the
eastern Santa Cruz province. Across all Bolivia there have been 270
suspected dengue infections, 47 of which have been confirmed.
In 2006 there were 1988 cases of classic dengue in Bolivia, or 21 per
100 000, with the vast majority reported in Santa Cruz.
[Byline Chen Feng]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The Beni province is often affected by seasonal rains and flooding.
The floods and the accompanying rains would be expected to increase
breeding sites for the mosquito vector. Vector control under these
circumstances would be difficult. Roads in the area often become
impassible during the rainy season. - Mod.TY]
